'''Robin Denise Smith''' (born October 9, 1964), better known by her [[ring name]] '''Rockin' Robin''', is a retired [[United States|American]] [[professional wrestler]]. As the daughter of [[Grizzly Smith|Aurelian "Grizzly" Smith]], she is a second-generation wrestler. Her brother [[Michael Smith (wrestler)|Sam Houston]] and half-brother [[Jake Roberts|Jake "The Snake" Roberts]] are also wrestlers. Smith worked for the [[World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) in the 1980s. She held the [[WWE Women's Championship|WWF Women's Championship]] from October 1988 until it was retired in 1990. She then worked on the [[independent circuit]].

==Professional wrestling career==

===World Wrestling Federation===
Smith grew up in a wrestling family and enjoyed going to wrestling shows, where she claims she and her siblings were treated like celebrities.<ref name=family/> Smith later decided to become a professional wrestler and trained, along with her sister-in-law [[Nickla Roberts]] (known by her [[ring name]] Baby Doll), under Nelson Royal.<ref name=cac/><ref name=baby/> During 1987, Smith competed as Rockin' Robin in Wild West Wrestling, where she feuded with [[Debbie Combs]] and [[Sue Green]]. When the WWF decided to restart their women's division in the late 1980s, both women tried out for the company, but the role ultimately went to Smith.<ref name=baby/> Smith, as Rockin' Robin, debuted in the WWF in late 1987.<ref name=encyclopedia>{{cite book|title=WWE Encyclopedia|author=Shields, Brian and Kevin Sullivan|publisher=DK/BradyGAMES|year=2009|isbn=978-0-7566-4190-0|page=152}}</ref> She competed at the first [[Survivor Series (1987)|Survivor Series]] as a member of [[The Fabulous Moolah]]'s team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/survivorseries/history/1987/results/|title=Surivor Series 1987: Results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2007-11-24}}</ref> Throughout 1988, she feuded with [[Sherri Martel|Sensational Sherri]] for the [[WWE Women's Championship|WWF Women's Championship]].<ref name=cac/>

On October 7, 1988, she defeated Sensational Sherri, who had held the title for fifteen months prior, for the Women's Championship in [[Paris]].<ref name=champ>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/titlehistory/women/30445413212111223|title=Women's Championship reign|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2007-11-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/06/15/4263993.html|title=Sherri Martel dead at 49|author=Oliver, Greg|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2008-11-01|date=June 15, 2007}}</ref><ref name=moolah>{{cite book|author=Ellison, Lillian|title=The Fabulous Moolah: First Goddess of the Squared Circle|year=2003|isbn=978-0-06-001258-8|publisher=ReaganBooks|page=197}}</ref> At the [[Royal Rumble (1989)|Royal Rumble]] in 1989, she defended the title against [[Judy Martin (wrestler)|Judy Martin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/royalrumble/history/1988115/results/|title=Royal Rumble 1989: Results|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|accessdate=2007-11-24}}</ref> Smith defended the belt against Martin for the first six months of 1989.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/08/06/4397845.html|title=Return of a "Glamour Girl"|author=Johnson, Steven|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2008-11-01|date=August 8, 2007}}</ref> In the meantime, at [[WrestleMania V]], she sang "[[America the Beautiful]]" to open the show.<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=champ/> Smith continued to defend the Women's title against Martin throughout the summer of 1989. She held the championship until 1990, when she left the company, and the title was retired by the WWF due to inactivity she still has the belt to this date.<ref name=champ/><ref name=moolah/> The title remained inactive until 1993.<ref name=encyclopedia/><ref name=champ/>

===Independent circuit===
Unlike some former WWF wrestlers, Smith was able to continue using her ring name after leaving the company because she owned the rights to it.<ref>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas'', p.190.</ref> In 1990, wrestler [[Hiro Matsuda]] picked Smith to tour for [[All Japan Women's Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=cac/> In Japan, Smith teamed with [[Luna Vachon]].<ref name=cac/> The Japanese [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Book|bookers]] gave the girls a positive review for their work with the company.<ref name=piranhas403/>

In the United States, Smith defeated [[Peggy Lee Leather]] for the [[Ladies Major League Wrestling]]'s International Championship.<ref name=cac/> She still occasionally defended the WWF Women's Championship, even though the title was officially declared vacant by the World Wrestling Federation. In May 1991 she defended the WWF Women's Championship against "[[IWA World Women's Championship|Japanese Women's Champion]]" [[Debra Miceli|Madusa Miceli]] on a Great Lakes Wrestling Association event.<ref name=Booking>{{cite web |url=http://www.athletepromotions.com/athletes/Rockin-Robin-appearance-booking-agent.php |title=Request Info for Booking Rockin Robin Appearance |accessdate=2011-08-29 |publisher=Athlete Promotions.com }}</ref> On June 9, 1991, she defeated [[Candi Devine]] in [[Herb Abrams]]'s [[Universal Wrestling Federation (Herb Abrams)|Universal Wrestling Federation]] to become the first UWF Women's Champion at [[UWF Beach Brawl]].<ref name=cac/> She also competed in the [[Ladies Professional Wrestling Association]] (LPWA), forming a tag team with [[Wendi Richter]].<ref name=cac/> She competed at LPWA's only pay-per-view, [[LPWA Super Ladies Showdown]].<ref name=cac/>

==Personal life==
Smith and her brother [[Michael Smith (wrestler)|Sam Houston]] are the children of [[Grizzly Smith|Aurelian "Grizzly" Smith]] and were born after his first marriage dissolved.<ref name=dead>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2010/06/12/14368776.html|title=Grizzly Smith dies at 77|author=Johnson, Steven and Greg Oliver|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2010-06-15|date=June 12, 2010}}</ref> Her half-brother is [[Jake Roberts|Jake "The Snake" Roberts]], who was born during their father's first marriage.<ref name=dead/> Robin and her brothers all wrestled in the WWF at the same time in the 1980s, but their relationship was never mentioned on-screen at the request of Robin.<ref name=family>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/12/07/12065306.html|title=Family matters in pro wrestling|author=Van Der Griend, Blaine|publisher=SLAM! Wrestling|accessdate=2010-06-15|date=December 10, 2009}}</ref> Author and former [[National Wrestling Alliance]] president Howard Brody alleges in his book ''Swimming with Piranhas'' that Robin was a victim of sexual abuse at the hands of her father.<ref name=dead/> According to Brody, Robin was removed from her father's care when her mother discovered what had been happening.<ref name=dead/>

After leaving the WWF in 1990, Smith was married to a man named Harvey Zitron.<ref name=piranhas403/> After divorcing, she moved to Louisiana and opened a telemarketing company that sold industrial chemicals and precious metals.<ref name=cac/><ref name=piranhas403/> Later, she opened a real estate appraisal business.<ref name=cac/> During this time, Smith had a drinking problem but eventually was able to quit altogether.<ref name=piranhas403/>

In 2005, Smith's home and all of her belongings were destroyed by [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref name=piranhas403>Brody, Howard. ''Swimming with Piranhas'', p.403<U+2013>405.</ref> During the aftermath of the hurricane, she stayed with family in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana]].<ref name=piranhas403/> She now runs a real estate appraisal business in Hammond, Louisiana [http://www.caulifloweralleyclub.org/2011/01/12/2011-womens-wrestling-award-rockin-robin/].

